Title:
Turn on cloud protection in Microsoft Defender Antivirus

Type:
Documentation

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This Microsoft Learn article explains how to enable and manage cloud-delivered protection (MAPS) in Microsoft Defender Antivirus and why it should remain enabled.  
- It highlights Defender for Endpoint capabilities that depend on cloud protection, including metadata-based ML lookups, automatic sample submission/detonation, Block at First Sight, emergency signature updates, EDR in block mode, certain ASR rules, and IoC-based allow/block actions.  
- The doc details multiple configuration paths: Microsoft Intune AV policies, Group Policy (MAPS membership and sample submission), PowerShell (`Set-MpPreference`), WMI (`MSFT_MpPreference`), and per-endpoint toggles via the Windows Security app.  
- It calls out operational constraints like Tamper Protection (which can ignore local changes) and the need for Troubleshooting Mode to temporarily allow modifications.  
- Useful primarily for blue teams and endpoint administrators standardizing Defender posture, but also relevant to red teams for understanding which Defender protections are cloud-dependent and what configuration controls/guardrails (tamper protection, policy enforcement) exist.

Technical Focus:
- Microsoft Defender Antivirus cloud-delivered protection (MAPSReporting)
- Automatic sample submission / SubmitSamplesConsent
- Intune Endpoint Security Antivirus policy configuration
- Group Policy (Defender Antivirus > MAPS) enforcement and local override behavior
- PowerShell Defender cmdlets (`Set-MpPreference`) and WMI (`MSFT_MpPreference`)
- Dependencies: Block at First Sight, ASR rules, EDR in block mode, IoCs, emergency intelligence updates

Use Cases:
- Enable/standardize cloud protection across Windows fleets via Intune or GPO
- Configure sample submission behavior to balance privacy vs detection efficacy
- Validate why certain MDE features (BAFS, some ASR rules, IoCs) aren’t functioning due to disabled cloud protection
- Automate Defender configuration in scripts using PowerShell/WMI
- Troubleshoot blocked configuration changes when Tamper Protection is enabled

Keywords:
Microsoft Defender Antivirus, Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, cloud protection, cloud-delivered protection, MAPS, MAPSReporting, SubmitSamplesConsent, automatic sample submission, Block at First Sight, tamper protection, troubleshooting mode, Intune, Group Policy, Set-MpPreference, MSFT_MpPreference, WMI, ASR rules, EDR in block mode, emergency signature updates, indicators of compromise, Windows Security app